# PR Quality Checklist

Process and quality items to follow for every PR. Complements the style, portability, allocation,
and project-structure rules defined in sibling rule files.

## Implementation

- **Safe first, then unsafe.** Implement with safe code. Benchmark it. Then explore
  `Unsafe.Add` / `MemoryMarshal` optimizations in release builds (`#if !DEBUG`). Document the
  before/after numbers. Only keep the unsafe path if it measurably helps.
- **Struct generic callbacks.** Use `where T : struct, IFoo` for hot-path callbacks — no
  interface dispatch, no boxing. Follow the `IRefCountHandler` / `IArenaNode` pattern.
- **SingleThreadedOwner.** Add debug-time thread ownership assertions on types designed for
  single-threaded use. Catches cross-thread misuse without runtime cost in release.
- **TestAccessor pattern.** Expose internals to tests via a nested `TestAccessor` struct
  returned by `GetTestAccessor()`. Never widen visibility of the type itself.
- **Internal visibility.** Keep building-block types `internal`. Only promote to `public` when
  required by another assembly.

## Allocations

- **No allocations in hot loops.** Do not `new` objects inside frequently-called methods. Use
  fields for reusable scratch space (arrays, lists, stacks). Verify with `[MemoryDiagnoser]`
  in benchmarks.
- **EnsureCapacity upfront.** Pre-allocate slab/array capacity before entering hot loops to
  avoid mid-loop growth checks and array copies.

## Code Quality

- **Reuse existing types.** Before creating a new collection or helper, check if
  `UnsafeStack<T>`, `UnsafeSlabDirectory<T>`, `SlabSizeHelper<T>`, or similar already solve
  the need.
- **Avoid code duplication.** Extract shared logic into private helpers or shared internal types.
  Large copy-pasted blocks across types are not acceptable.
- **dotnet format.** Run `dotnet format --verify-no-changes` after every substantive change. Fix
  violations immediately — do not leave them for a later pass.

## Testing

- **Comprehensive tests.** Cover edge cases and permutations. Use `[Theory]` with `[InlineData]`
  for parameterized variations. Prefer programmatic generation of test cases over hand-coded
  permutations.
- **Benchmarks.** Use production-default parameters. Run with BenchmarkDotNet and
  `[MemoryDiagnoser]`. Record results in `benchmarks/results/<date>/`. Add a brief summary in
  source doc comments pointing to the results directory.

## Documentation

- **Research and plans.** Write research docs in `research/<date>/`, plans in `plans/<date>/`.
  Do this for every non-trivial PR.
- **Portability notes.** On new types, include a brief `PORTABILITY` section in the doc comment
  explaining how the type maps to Rust/C++.
